Carbon is without any suspicion the most adaptable element known to man, because of the fact it is the foundation of life on earth. Carbon is the fundamental construction unit of all organic chemistry and of the 20 million known molecules. Graphene is a carbon allotropic form which consist of carbon atoms forming a monolayer [1]. All graphite materials are formed from graphene. The length bond of carbon bonded atom is 0.142Â nm [2]. Layers of graphene arranged together forming graphite with inter-planer distance of 0.33Â nm [3]. The sheets are stick together by Vander-wallâs interaction which can be further exfoliated by different methods [4]. The thinness material known to man is graphene about single atom thick, the mild material recognized with 1Â m2 weighing about 0.77Â mg and the strongest material ever found about 300 times stronger than steel [5]. Despite of the invincibleness graphene is an good conductor of heat, electricity and optically transparent [6, 7]. Because of the amazing characteristics graphene has been selected for a broad range of applications ranging from electronics to optics bio-devices and sensors [8â10]. Recently Nano-technologists are quite enthusiastic about graphene. Scientists have been studied that graphene has the ability to conduct electricity even at zero carrier concentration because of Heisenberg uncertainty principles [11]. The electron buzzing around the carbon atom which interact with the periodic potential of graphene hexagonal lattice [12] which produce new quasi-particles thatâs why graphene never stop conducting. The reasons that makes graphene interesting both as individual and as composites is due to the outstanding properties such as stiffness, strength [13] and toughness [14]. Throughout the world research groups working on the development of industrially fabricated graphene layers that have high stiffness used as graphene based composites for optoelectronics and neural implants [15, 16]. Graphene is the first 2D